<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-10-28T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-10-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="854" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d854">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72119/2261</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                    to the Serbian Chargé</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Simitch</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-10-28">
                                        <hi rend="italic">October 28, 1918</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I beg to acknowledge the receipt of
                                your note of October 14,<note n="1" xml:id="d854fn1">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_842">p.
                                    842</ref>.</note> requesting a declaration by the United States,
                                and the other countries at war with Germany, in favor of the freedom
                                of the Serbs, Croats and Slovenes of Austria-Hungary and their union
                                with Serbia in a free and democratic state, such as was provided for
                                in the Declaration of Corfu.</p>
                            <p>In reply I beg to state that the United States has expressed itself
                                freely in support of the right of the Jugo-Slavs to be entirely
                                freed from Austrian domination and that at the present time it does
                                not feel that it can go further in declaring a policy which
                                manifestly depends upon the self-determination of the peoples
                                involved.</p>
                            <p>Accept [etc.]</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert Lansing</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>